description.narrative:
Micro and small-scale industries are critically important for the sustainable socio-economic development of the island.

Development of vibrant agro processing enterprises can increase significantly market demands and revenue flow and reduce post-harvest loss of farm crops. However, the main obstacles that are claiming a high toll to the agro-industry linkages are notably:

• irregular and insufficient supply of raw materials;
• poor quality of raw materials and high post-harvest losses;
• outdated/traditional agro processing and marketing practices;
• inadequate enabling conditions including food safety and good hygiene practices;
• lack of effective dialogue and consultation between public and private stakeholders;
• underutilization of existing human, technical and financial resources;
• absence of climate change resilience strategies.

An example for this situation is the lemon sector. There is a relative large quantity of lemon production on the Rodrigues Island but over 75 percent of the production of lemon is not harvested and are therefore wasted during peak seasons while there is a shortage of the same during low seasons. In addition the sector is not structured and there has been little initiative toward creating value added products.

A major challenge for market development of the Rodriguan agro foods is the absence good hygiene practices. The Food Act 1998 is currently not enforced in Rodrigues. Most agro processing is performed in domestic kitchens, which operate without permission.

The Regional Authority of Rodrigues Island (RRA) requests UNIDO to provide technical assistance.

The objective of the requested is:
To develop the lemon sector as a source for increased income and to contribute to RRA’s development goals in terms of poverty reduction, food security, employment creation, climate change resilience and social stability.

Expected outputs:
• Model for sector restructuring developed
• Post harvest losses reduced
• Processing technologies improved
• Market access increased
• Women cooperatives strengthened
